# void farm

This BP/AI will alternate Temporal Barrier and Void casts to survive/kill while casting Rak's Curse until Void's cooldown is low enough (detected automatically) to run constnatly.

It will then transition to constantly casting void, while still running Temporal Barrier (and Immortality Shield) to keep tank up as much as possible to guard against lag spikes

It tries to maximize contract fulfillment and uses Magical Stone of Floof (etc...) to get good resource returns.  Since it also can push very high infs, it should also be decent at fragment farming.

The AI should tolerate toggling off and on while running but may cause some unwanted behavior (variable hiding, stats will be off if you have a Rak's Curse stack already), so I wouldn't recommend it.

"Luck" is also tracked in global `raks_log` with the format `stacks earned`:`casts`:`time (seconds)` each time the tower dies

## Town Setup

Perks: Resource Drops / Town Assets / Power Stones 1:1:1 (if not even, prioritze in order listed, with no more than 1 level difference, ie 41/41/40)

Anvil: Town Resources or Town XP Factor are good, Module cooldown can help a lot to reduce needed Rak's Curse stacks.

Infinity Stones: Anvil Fragments \^1.1, resource drops x10,000 recommended


## configuration

If you edit the BP you can correct active module slots in the `globals` script.  There's other stuff in there you can move outside the hide block if you want to see it, or you can hide some other variables.  I like to keep `rak-stack` visible because the overlay still updates with dynamic rendering turned on (might be a bug though)

By default, Rak's Curse will stop casing once Void has a low enough cooldown, but you can change that behavior by changing `target cd`.  You can even change what module cooldown its looking at with `target cd var` (valid entries are `"void cd"` `"barrier cd"` note void and floof have the same cooldown).  The script will still switch to constant void casting at the normal time.

For the module CD variables, these are updated while running but void/barrier set properly can allow you to restart the script in the middle of a run with a good chanse of not breaking completely.  Note that the game always rounds the displayed cooldown value down, so I recommend adding 1.

## Technical Details

Rak's Curse is pretty energy intensive, so normally you do not want to cast it when an important spell is coming up (~5s window).  This is why I included Recharge.  I still avoid casting if its about to cast (0.1s window) so an unlucky situation won't make it cast just after Recharge but before Void.  Similar logic is used in the 2nd phase with Immortality Shield.

There's safety margins built in for lag (ie 29.8s instead of 30) and protection from expecting negative CD values (`max(..., 0.0)` etc).  Many modules are included just for lag death prevention, prior to adding I could fairly reliably cause a lag death by maximizing from a small window when TB was not up.

For a breakdown on modules and contracts see [modules.md](modules.md)
